  "text": "Mice carrying a homozygous targeted deletion of ZEB1 die close to birth with cleft palate and a number of bone and cartilage abnormalities [CITATION_1] . Although at embryonic days 10 to 11, levels of MyoD, myogenin, and MCK are not significantly affected in these mice [CITATION_2] , a molecular analysis of muscle differentiation at later stages has not been carried out. From the results shown up to here, one might expect that the temporal pattern of expression of muscle differentiation gene expression would be accelerated in ZEB1 Ϫ/Ϫ mouse embryos. Of all adult MHC isoforms, IIb/MyH4 is induced not only the Ϫ/Ϫ embryos than in the ZEB1 ϩ/ϩ sibling counterparts, where it was barely detectable. (D) Schematic model of the role of endogenous ZEB1 regulating the temporal pattern of gene expression during muscle differentiation. In myoblasts, ZEB1 binds to G/C-centered E-boxes in the regulatory regions of muscle differentiation genes whose transcription would be repressed at least in part via recruitment of CtBP. In myotubes, MyoD would displace ZEB1 from these G/C-centered E-boxes, thus activating the expression of muscle genes as differentiation progresses. earliest (around E14.5) but also at much higher levels than the rest, while mRNA for isoform IIa/MyH2 starts to be detected only after E17.5 [CITATION_3] . We decided to examine by immunohistochemistry the expression of both adult MHC isoforms during late development in sibling mouse embryos that were either wild type (ϩ/ϩ) or null (Ϫ/Ϫ) for ZEB1. We found that by E18.5, expression of MyH4 was only slightly higher in ZEB1 Ϫ/Ϫ embryos than in the normal ZEB1 ϩ/ϩ sibling counterparts (Fig. 6B) . Meanwhile, MyH2, which was barely detectable in ZEB1 ϩ/ϩ mouse embryos, displayed earlier (higher) expression in the ZEB1 Ϫ/Ϫ sibling counterpart embryos (Fig. 6C) . These results, consistent with the cellbased and in vivo data described above, indicate that loss of ZEB1 results in an acceleration of the temporal pattern of the muscle differentiation gene signature.",
